[Patient] How much water should I drink every day to manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for around 8 cups of water daily, but adjust based on your doctor's advice.
[Patient] Can I drink other fluids besides water?
[Educator] Yes, but limit drinks high in sugar or caffeine as they can worsen heart failure symptoms.
[Patient] How do I know if I'm drinking too much fluid?
[Educator] Watch for sudden weight gain, swelling, or increased shortness of breath.
[Patient] What should I do if I notice these symptoms?
[Educator] Contact your doctor immediately and follow their guidance on managing fluid intake.
[Patient] Can I still exercise if I have heart failure?
[Educator] Yes, but start slowly and avoid intense activities that may strain your heart.
[Patient] How can I remember to track my fluid intake daily?
[Educator] Consider using a journal or app to record your fluids and set reminders.
[Patient] Should I avoid salt in my diet to help with fluid intake?
[Educator] Yes, reducing salt can help control fluid retention and improve heart failure symptoms.
[Patient] Is it okay to drink alcohol with heart failure?
[Educator] Limit alcohol intake as it can worsen heart failure symptoms and interact with medications.
[Patient] Thank you for the advice, it's helpful to understand how to manage my fluid intake better.
[Educator] You're welcome! Remember to stay consistent and communicate any concerns with your healthcare team.